<B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P ALIGN="CENTER">Logic</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">Learning Plan 4</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">Propositional Logic (Implication)</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial">
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>For students on module MATM153, the lecture notes referred to in this Learning Plan are those entitled &quot;Boolean Algebra&quot;.</P>


<P>If p and q are two propositions, then the proposition </P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">&quot;if p then q&quot;</P>

<P>is an <B>implication</B> and the connective &quot;if …….. then&quot; the <B>conditional</B> <B>connective</B>&quot;.</P>

<P>The conditional connective is denoted by <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 and the implication is read as </P>
<B><P ALIGN="CENTER">p implies q.</P>
</B><P>Here p is called the hypothesis and q the conclusion.   The conditional p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 q can be read as :-</P>

<br>
<UL>
<LI>p implies q</LI>
<LI>p is sufficient for q</LI>
<LI>p only if q</LI>
<LI>q is necessary for p</LI></UL>

<br>
<P>The truth table for an implication is:</P>
<img src="Image88.png">
</FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial">




<br>
<P>Think of  p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 q as a conditional promise.   If the promise is broken then the implication is False, otherwise it is True.</P>

<B><P>Note</P>
</B><P>From the truth table we always guarantee that p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 q is true by choosing p to be false.</P>

<B><P>Example 1</P>
</B><P>Consider the two propositions:</P>
<P>p : you pass Maths</P>
<P>q: you receive £1000</P>
<P>p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 q : If you pass Maths then you receive £1000.</P>

